{{Infobox Treaty |image = |image_width = |caption = |name = Budgetary Treaty of 1970 |long_name = Treaty amending Certain Budgetary Provisions of the Treaties establishing the European Communities and of the Treaty establishing a Single Council and a Single Commission of the European Communities |type = |date_draft = |date_signed = 22 April 1970 |location_signed = [[Luxembourg (city)|Luxembourg City]], [[Luxembourg]] |date_sealed = |date_effective = 1 January 1971 |date_expiration = |signatories = [[Inner Six|The Six]] |depositor = |language = |languages = |wikisource = }} {{Infobox Treaty |image = |image_width = |caption = |name = Budgetary Treaty of 1975 |long_name = Treaty amending Certain Financial Provisions of the Treaty establishing the European Communities and of the Treaty establishing a Single Council and a Single Commission of the European Communities |type = |date_draft = |date_signed = 22 July 1975 |location_signed = [[Brussels]], [[Belgium]] |date_sealed = |date_effective = 1 June 1977 |date_expiration = |signatories = [[Member State of the European Union|All then-9 EC members]] |depositor = |language = |languages = |wikisource = }} The '''Budgetary treaties of the European Communities''' were two treaties in the 1970s amending the [[Treaty of Rome]] in respects to powers over the [[Budget of the European Union|Community budget]].
The first treaty, signed in 1970, gave the [[European Parliament]] the last word on what is known as "non-compulsory expenditure" (compulsory spending is that resulting from [[Treaties of the European Union|EC treaties]] (including [[Common Agricultural Policy|agriculture]]) and international agreements; the rest is non-compulsory). The second treaty, signed in 1975, gave Parliament the power to reject the budget as a whole and created the [[European Court of Auditors]]. However, the Council still has the last word on compulsory spending while Parliament has the last word on non-compulsory spending.<ref name="budgetary power">{{cite web|title = Budgetary power|publisher=[[Europa (web portal)|European Parliament]]|url=http://www.europarl.europa.eu/parliament/public/staticDisplay.do?id=46&pageRank=5&language=EN|accessdate = 2007-06-12 }}</ref><ref name="budget decided">{{cite web|title=How is the budget decided?|publisher=[[Europa (web portal)|European Parliament]]|url=http://ec.europa.eu/budget/budget_glance/how_decided_en.htm|accessdate=2007-06-12|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070520130739/http://ec.europa.eu/budget/budget_glance/how_decided_en.htm#|archive-date=2007-05-20|dead-url=yes|df=}}</ref>
As a result of these treaties, the budgetary authority of what is now the [[European Union]] is held jointly by the [[Council of the European Union]] and the [[European Parliament]]. Parliament is responsible for discharging the implementation of previous budgets, on the basis of the annual report of the [[European Court of Auditors]]. It has refused to approve the budget only twice, in 1984 and in 1998. On the latter occasion it led to the resignation of the [[Santer Commission]].<ref name="budget background">{{cite web | title=Budgetary control: 1996 discharge raises issue of confidence in the Commission | publisher =[[Europa (web portal)]]| year=1999 | url =http://www.europarl.europa.eu/election/bilan/en/pf1901en.htm | accessdate = 2007-10-15 }}</ref>
