{{Taxobox | name = Halmahera blossom bat | image = | status = VU | status_system = IUCN3.1 | status_ref=<ref name="iucn 2008">{{cite journal| last1=Helgen| first1= K.| last2= Salas| first2= L.| year= 2008| title= Syconycteris carolinae| journal= The IUCN Red List of Threatened Species| volume= 2008| page= e.T21184A9247354| url= https://dx.doi.org/10.2305/IUCN.UK.2008.RLTS.T21184A9247354.en}}</ref> | regnum = [[Animal]]ia | phylum = [[Chordata]] | classis = [[Mammal]]ia | ordo = [[Chiroptera]] | familia = [[Pteropodidae]] | genus = ''[[Syconycteris]]'' | species = '''''S. carolinae''''' | binomial = ''Syconycteris carolinae'' | binomial_authority = Rozendaal, 1984 | synonyms = | range_map = Halmahera Blossom Bat area.png | range_map_caption = Halmahera blossom bat range }}
The '''Halmahera blossom bat''' (''Syconycteris carolinae'') is a [[species]] of [[megabat]] in the family [[Pteropodidae]].
The bat is [[endemic]] to [[Halmahera]] and [[Bacan]] islands, of the northern [[Maluku Islands]] archipelago in [[Indonesia]]. It is an [[IUCN Red List]] [[Vulnerable species]] because: its extent of occurrence is less than 20,000&nbsp;km²; it is known only from three locations; and there is ongoing decline in the extent and quality of its habitat due to intensified [[habitat loss|habitat destruction]]. A 2017 study ranked the species as the 8th highest research priority among island endemic bats based on conservation situation and current data availability.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Conenna|first=Irene|last2=Rocha|first2=Ricardo|last3=Russo|first3=Danilo|last4=Cabeza|first4=Mar|date=2017-04-17|title=Insular bats and research effort: a review of global patterns and priorities|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.1111/mam.12090|journal=Mammal Review|volume=47|issue=3|pages=169–182|doi=10.1111/mam.12090|issn=0305-1838}}</ref>
