{{Infobox scientist | name = Jane Rumble | image = Jane Rumble.jpg | nationality = [[United Kingdom|Britain]] | workplaces = Polar Regions Department, [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]], UK | alma_mater = [[University of Exeter]] }}
'''Jane Rumble''' is the Head of the Polar Regions Department for the UK’s [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]].<ref name=":0">{{Cite web|url=http://www.arcticfrontiers.com/arctic-frontiers/archive/2014-conference/policy-section/keynote-speakers/198-jane-rumble-head-of-polar-region-department-foreign-and-commonwealth-office-uk|title=Arctic Frontiers - Jane Rumble, Head of Polar Regions Department, Foreign and Commonwealth Office, UK|last=Emblow|first=Chris|website=www.arcticfrontiers.com|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://publications.parliament.uk/pa/cm201314/cmselect/cmsctech/uc103-i/uc103.pdf|title=Marine Protected Areas in the Southern Ocean|last=|first=|date=2013|website=|publisher=[[House of Commons]]|access-date=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://jncc.defra.gov.uk/PDF/ot_biodiversity2011_britishantarticterritory.pdf|title=British Antarctic Territory|last=|first=|date=|website=jncc.defra.gov.uk/|publisher=Polar Regions Unit, Foreign and Commonwealth Office and British Antarctic Survey|access-date=}}</ref>
==Early life and education== Rumble attended [[Aylesbury]] High School and subsequently graduated with a BSc in Geography from the [[University of Exeter]].{{citation needed|date=June 2016}}
==Career and impact== Rumble was appointed to the position of Head of Polar Regions Department in January 2007, having been Deputy Head since 2003.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1">{{Cite web|url=http://www.csap.cam.ac.uk/network/jane-rumble/|title=Jane Rumble - Sciences & technology in the service of society|website=www.csap.cam.ac.uk|access-date=2016-06-04}}</ref> She began her civil service career in the UK’s [[Department of Environment]], where she held a number of roles dealing with corporate and environmental policy, including policy on the health and safety of genetically modified crops.<ref name=":1" /> She then worked for the cross-Whitehall [[Teenage pregnancy in the United Kingdom|Teenage Pregnancy Unit]] before joining the [[Foreign and Commonwealth Office]], where she began to work on polar policy. Rumble is the fourth Head of the FCO's polar regions department since 1943.<ref name=":0" /><ref name=":1" /> During her time as the Head of Polar Regions, she has been involved in shaping policy relevant to Arctic and Antarctic protection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://energyblog.nationalgeographic.com/2013/09/20/forum-on-arctic-science-of-change-focuses-on-decisions-at-the-top-of-the-world/|title=Forum on Arctic ‘Science of Change’ Focuses on Decisions at the Top of the World|last=Lavelle|first=Marianne|date=2013-09-21|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=P0vgwKtIlEwC|title=Protecting the Arctic|last=Environmental Audit Committee|first=|date=2012-09-20|publisher=House of Commons|isbn=9780215048394|volume=1|language=}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.rgs.org/OurWork/Schools/Why+Does+Antarctica+Matter.htm|title=Why Does Antarctica Matter?|website=www.rgs.org|publisher=[[Royal Geographical Society]]|access-date=2016-06-21}}</ref>
==Awards and honors== Rumble is a Fellow of the [[Royal Geographical Society]] and a Policy Fellow with the Centre for Science and Policy, [[University of Cambridge]].<ref name=":1" />
She was appointed as an Officer of the Order of the British Empire (awarded an OBE) in the 2018 Queen’s Birthday Honours List.<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=62310|date=9 June 2018 |page=B23 |supp=y}}</ref> In July 2018 she was made an honorary [[Doctor of Science]] by Leeds University.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.leeds.ac.uk/info/130509/honorary_graduates/646/jane_frances_rumble |title=Jane Frances Rumble |publisher=University of Leeds |date=July 2018 |accessdate=10 July 2018}}</ref>
